🧠 1. The CORE Problem in Your Data

👉 Your data is:

Cumulative ✔
But per state ✔

That means:

Each state has its own running total

❌ Why normal methods fail
Using SUM()
SUM(covid_table[Confirmed])

👉 Adds all days → double counting ❌

Using MAX()
MAX(covid_table[Confirmed])

👉 Picks only one state’s highest value ❌

🧠 2. What you ACTUALLY need

👉 You want:

“Latest total for each state → then add them”

🔥 3. Understanding the Solution
✅ This is the key formula:
SUMX(
    VALUES(covid_table[State]),
    CALCULATE(MAX(covid_table[Confirmed]))
)

Let’s break it 👇

🧩 4. Each Part Explained
🔹 VALUES(covid_table[State])

👉 Gives:

Kerala  
Maharashtra  
Tamil Nadu  
...

✔ Unique list of states

🔹 SUMX(...)

👉 Means:

“Loop through each state and sum results”

🔹 Inside SUMX:
CALCULATE(MAX(covid_table[Confirmed]))

👉 For each state:

CALCULATE applies filter → current state
MAX gets latest cumulative value
🧠 So overall:

👉 For every state:

Take latest confirmed
Then add all states

✔ Correct total

🧠 5. Final Measures (Clean Understanding)
🔹 Total Confirmed
Total Confirmed =
SUMX(
    VALUES(covid_table[State]),
    CALCULATE(MAX(covid_table[Confirmed]))
)

👉 Output:

Total confirmed across all states (correct)

🔹 Total Recovered
Total Recovered =
SUMX(
    VALUES(covid_table[State]),
    CALCULATE(MAX(covid_table[Recovered]))
)
🔹 Total Deaths
Total Deaths =
SUMX(
    VALUES(covid_table[State]),
    CALCULATE(MAX(covid_table[Deaths]))
)
🧠 6. Now KPI Measures
🔹 Recovery Rate
Recovery Rate =
DIVIDE(
    [Total Recovered],
    [Total Confirmed],
    BLANK()
)
🔹 Death Rate
Death Rate =
DIVIDE(
    [Total Deaths],
    [Total Confirmed],
    BLANK()
)
